io-Instruct              1.28       2.42       18.19      12.25        10.25             3.53           2.90            8.06       6.62\n Voxtral-Small-24B-2507           1.59       3.26       15.27      10.50        9.81              2.02           3.52            6.96       6.62\n MiMo-Audio                       3.50         –          –          –            –                 –              –               –          –\n...\n</persisted-output>", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d", "uuid": "00f30877-ffb3-4ff3-8a54-70ae5703c63e", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:42:04.240Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "\f                                 Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\nTable 8: WER (↓) Evaluation Results on OpenASR Leaderboard (English).\n\n Models                          LS-clean   LS-other    AMI     Earnings22    GigaSpeech       SPGI Speech   TED-LIUM          VoxPopuli   Average\n Whisper-large-v3                 2.01       3.91       15.95      11.29        10.02             2.94           3.86            9.54       7.44\n Canary-1B-v2                     2.18       3.56       16.01      11.79        10.82             2.28           4.29            6.25       7.15\n Parakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3             1.92       3.59       11.39      11.19        9.57              3.98           2.80            6.09       6.32\n Canary Qwen 2.5B                 1.61       3.10       10.19      10.45        9.43              1.90           2.71            5.66       5.63\n Step-Audio-R1.1 33B              1.66       3.28       22.36      11.54        9.97              3.80           3.03            7.60       7.91\n Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct      1.28       2.52       11.44      10.47        8.79              2.44           2.78            6.07       5.72\n Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Thinking      1.77       3.70       25.19      10.51        9.49              3.47           2.38            7.52       8.00\n Qwen3.5-Omni Flash               1.30       2.43         –          –            –                 –              –               –          –\n Kimi-Audio-Instruct              1.28       2.42       18.19      12.25        10.25             3.53           2.90            8.06       6.62\n Voxtral-Small-24B-2507           1.59       3.26       15.27      10.50        9.81              2.02           3.52            6.96       6.62\n MiMo-Audio                       3.50         –          –          –            –                 –              –               –          –\n Audex 30B-A3B                    1.34       3.06       17.24      11.92         9.90             1.76           3.50            5.83       6.82\n Audex 2B                         1.63       3.77       17.10      11.95        10.86             2.00           3.64            6.17       7.14\n\n\nTable 9: WER (↓) Evaluation Results on Noisy Librispeech ASR at different noise levels.\n\n                 Models                                -5dB     0dB    5dB    10dB   25dB        50dB    100dB     Average\n                 Whisper-large-v3                      9.30     4.24   2.72   2.27      2.15     1.98    1.97           3.52\n                 Canary-1B-v2                          19.38    5.08   2.80   2.29      2.01     2.16    2.18           5.13\n                 Parakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3                  12.21    4.82   2.62   2.15      1.96     1.92    1.92           3.94\n                 Canary Qwen 2.5B                      11.06    4.73   2.50   2.91      1.64     1.61    1.61           3.58\n                 Step-Audio-R1.1 33B                   9.74     4.05   2.74   3.55      1.72     1.69    1.61           3.59\n                 Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct           7.43     2.75   1.74   1.49      1.34     1.28    1.26           2.47\n                 Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Thinking           8.63     3.66   2.29   1.95      1.72     1.69    1.64           3.08\n                 Kimi-Audio-Instruct                   9.81     3.86   2.06   1.60      1.47     1.35    1.33           3.07\n                 Voxtral-Small-24B-2507                8.39     3.68   2.20   1.87      1.61     1.58    1.59           2.99\n                 Audex 30B-A3B                         9.37     3.26   2.01   1.67      1.41     1.37    1.34           2.92\n                 Audex 2B                              10.60    4.02   2.41   1.97      1.66     1.60    1.63           3.41\n\n\n\n5.3. Results on Audio Understanding, ASR, and AST\nIn this section, we evaluate Audex on audio understanding, ASR, and AST tasks. All of these are formatted in\nthe audio question-answering template. For audio understanding tasks, the user question is defined in the\nspecific benchmark, and we use a top-p of 0.9 and temperature of 0.7. For ASR and AST tasks, we use fixed\nprompts in the user turn, and use greedy sampling.\n\nEnglish ASR Results\nThe evaluation results on OpenASR leaderboard (Srivastav et al., 2025) 10 are shown in Table 8. The results on\nnoisy LibriSpeech ASR evaluation following (Sekoyan et al., 2025) are shown in Table 9. For both benchmarks,\nwe report word error rate (WER) represented in percentage (the lower the better). Results show that Audex\nmatches strong audio-language model baselines and outperforms several strong ASR-specific baselines, especially\nin the noisy ASR setting. The gap between our 30B-A3B and 2B models is not huge, as the audio encoder\nperceives most of the information needed for transcribing.\n\nMulti-Lingual ASR and AST Results\nWe evaluate multi-lingual ASR and AST using the Fleurs benchmark (Conneau et al., 2023), and evaluate\non seven languages: DE (German), ES (Spanish), FR (French), IT (Italian), PT (Portuguese), RU (Russian),\nKO (Korean). We report the WER for multi-lingual ASR in Table 10, and BLEU (Papineni et al., 2002) and\nCOMET (Rei et al., 2020) scores for AST (the higher the better) in Table 11. Results show that Audex also has\nstrong multi-lingual ASR and AST abilities that are comparable to several state-of-the-art speech LLMs. 11\n\nAudio Understanding Results\nWe evaluate audio understanding quality with the following benchmarks:\n  10 https://huggingface.co/spaces/hf-audio/open_asr_leaderboard\n  11We report the average of these seven (noted as Fleurs-Multilingual and Fleurs (xx→en) ) in Table 1.\n                                                                      7                  7\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                   15\n\f                                 Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\nTable 10: WER (↓) Evaluation Results on Fleurs Multilingual ASR.\n\n                   Models                                  DE      ES      FR         IT     PT       RU       KO        Average\n                   Whisper-large-v3                        3.28   2.33     4.99   2.41       3.50    3.64      7.09       3.89\n                   Seamless-m4t-v2-large                   5.29   3.99     6.37   3.52       6.94    6.51     14.76       6.77\n                   Canary-1B-v2                            3.47   2.63     4.41   2.35       4.19    5.92        –          –\n                   Parakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3                    4.27   3.28     4.70   2.44       4.54    4.93        –          –\n                   Step-Audio-R1.1 33B                     5.49   3.74     6.72   3.25       5.36    9.84     11.75       6.59\n                   Voxtral-Small-24B-2507                  2.58   2.77     3.54   2.16       3.71    6.29     17.10       5.45\n                   Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct             2.47   2.34     3.35   1.55       3.07    3.15     19.85       5.11\n                   Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Thinking             3.40   2.71     4.46   2.52       3.73    5.81      7.29       4.27\n                   Audex 30B-A3B                           4.33   2.85     5.79   3.27       4.35    5.45     9.71        5.11\n                   Audex 2B                                5.98   3.71     6.89   4.22       4.93    8.74     10.22       6.38\n\n\nTable 11: Evaluation Results on Fleurs AST (xx→en) Using BLEU|COMET (↑).\n\n Models                               DE              ES             FR               IT             PT             RU             KO     Average\n Whisper-large-v3                  33.6|84.8    22.5|83.5         31.1|84.4     23.0|84.0         36.8|85.8    26.5|83.3     19.2|81.7    27.5|83.9\n Seamless-m4t-v2-large             36.8|86.0    25.7|84.2         33.9|85.2     26.8|85.0         37.4|85.0    30.2|83.9     22.8|83.5    30.5|84.7\n Canary-1B-v2                      35.2|85.4    25.2|83.3         33.7|85.2     25.1|84.2         38.6|85.4    27.0|81.6         –            –\n Step-Audio-R1.1 33B               38.0|88.2    26.8|86.4         36.2|87.3     26.7|86.7         41.7|87.7    30.2|85.1     26.4|86.8    32.3|86.9\n Voxtral-Small-24B-2507            43.9|89.0    34.8|87.5         42.6|88.6     35.2|88.0         48.7|89.2    37.2|86.6     26.6|85.7    41.0|88.5\n Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct       41.5|88.5    28.6|86.7         38.1|87.9     28.6|87.0         43.3|88.3    32.4|86.0     28.1|87.6    34.4|87.4\n Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Thinking       40.7|88.7    28.0|86.6         37.6|88.3     28.2|87.0         42.7|88.5    32.3|86.1     27.6|87.9    33.9|87.6\n Audex 30B-A3B                     40.0|88.0    28.5|86.1         38.0|87.1     29.0|86.8         43.4|88.0    32.8|85.3     26.3|86.9    34.0|86.9\n Audex 2B                          37.3|86.8    35.2|85.8         26.0|85.6     26.5|85.3         41.3|87.0    29.4|83.5     23.4|85.5    31.2|85.7\n\n\nTable 12: Audio Understanding Evaluation Results.\n\n                                                       MMAU                                                      Audio Entailment\n   Models                                                                                  MMAR     MMSU                                  CMM\n                                     mini      sound   music speech             avg                            Clotho v2 AudioCaps\n   Audio-Flamingo-3                  74.3      75.3        74.6     69.6      73.2         60.1      62.3        93.3              95.0   86.5\n   Step-Audio-R1.1 33B               76.8      76.4        68.9     75.6      73.6         69.8      74.1        59.3              63.7   83.3\n   Kimi-Audio-Instruct               68.2      70.7        65.9     56.6      64.4         57.4      59.3        62.4              65.3   67.0\n   Voxtral-Small-24B-2507            60.2      54.3        51.1     66.7      57.4         32.8      56.6        55.1              57.2   72.4\n   MiMo-Audio                        74.7      77.2        69.7     70.8      72.6         63.6      62.9        71.7              78.5   82.3\n   Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Instruct        –         –           –        –        77.5         67.9      69.0        66.8              68.8   90.4\n   Qwen3-Omni-30B-A3B-Thinking        –         –           –        –        75.4         66.4      70.2        60.4              62.8   85.0\n   Audex 30B-A3B                     76.5      81.5        77.5     67.9      75.6         63.2      63.4        94.4              95.6   90.3\n   Audex 2B                          72.1      75.1        72.3     61.8      69.7         56.8      57.6        93.2              92.9   75.9\n\n\n\n   • MMAU (v05.15.25) (Sakshi et al., 2024), MMAR (Ma et al., 2025), and MMSU (Wang et al., 2025b) for\n     general sound, speech, and music understanding. These test samples are all multiple choice questions.\n   • Audio Entailment (Deshmukh et al., 2024) on Clotho v2 and AudioCaps for deductive reasoning. 12 These\n     benchmarks contain closed-ended questions and require outputs to be within {yes, no, maybe}.\n   • CMM (Leng et al., 2026) for hallucination detection. This benchmark also contains closed-ended questions\n     with a focus on sound event existence, and requires outputs to be within {yes, no}.\n\nThe results are shown in Table 12. Audex matches strong baselines on MMAU, but has some gap on MMAR and\nMMSU compared to the state-of-the-art audio LLMs. Audex demonstrates strong results on audio entailment\nand CMM hallucination, which indicate better trustworthiness.\n\n5.4. Results on Speech Interaction\nWe evaluate speech interaction (speech-to-text and speech-to-speech) results via a cascaded system (ASR +\ntext reasoning + potential TTS), but different from most cascaded systems, we use the same Audex model\nwith suitable inference setups for all of these three steps. The results on BigBenchAudio are shown in Table 13.\n  12We report the average of these two (noted as Audio Entailment ) in Table 1.\n                                                                 2\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                 16\n\f                               Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nAudex 30B-A3B achieves a score of 90, which is very competitive on the benchmark. Audex 2B also outperforms\nseveral strong baselines that are 7B or larger. The results on VoiceBench are shown in Table 14. Audex is\ncompetitive especially on instruction following, reasoning, multiple choice QA, and safety.\n\nTable 13: Evaluation Results on BigBenchAudio.\n\n                                 Models                                           Accuracies\n                                 Fun-Realtime-Audiochat                              97.6\n                                 Step-Audio R1.1 Realtime                            97.6\n                                 Gemini 3.1 Flash Live Preview - High                96.6\n                                 Grok Voice Agent                                    93.3\n                                 Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Dialog Thinking       90.7\n                                 Nova 2.0 Sonic (Mar 2026)                           88.1\n                                 GPT Realtime                                        83.3\n                                 GPT-Realtime-1.5                                    81.4\n                                 Qwen3.5 Omni Plus Realtime                          73.0\n                                 Gemini 3.1 Flash Live Preview - Minimal             71.3\n                                 GPT-4o mini Realtime (Dec 2024)                     68.9\n                                 Gemini 2.5 Flash Native Audio Dialog                68.6\n                                 GPT Realtime Mini (Oct 2025)                        63.6\n                                 MiMo-Audio                                          60.2\n                                 Qwen3.5 Omni Flash Realtime                         59.0\n                                 Qwen3 Omni Flash                                    58.7\n                                 Qwen3 Omni Realtime                                 56.8\n                                 GPT-4o audio chatcompletions                        54.3\n                                 Kimi-Audio-Instruct                                 51.0\n                                 Nemotron VoiceChat                                  38.8\n                                 Freeze-Omni                                         33.4\n                                 PersonaPlex                                         19.1\n                                 FLM-Audio                                           16.0\n                                 Moshi                                                4.4\n                                 Audex 30B-A3B                                       90.0\n                                 Audex 2B                                            64.3\n\n\nTable 14: Evaluation Results on VoiceBench.\n\n Models                        AlpacaEval   CommonEval     WildVoice   SD-QA     MMSU    OpenBookQA   BBH    IFEval   AdvBench\n Qwen3-Omni 30B-A3B Instruct      94.8          90.8          91.6      76.9     68.1          89.7   80.4   77.8      99.3\n Qwen3-Omni 30B-A3B Thinking      96.4          90.5          90.5      78.1     83.0          94.3   88.9   80.6      97.2\n Ultravox-GLM-4P7                 97.4          86.0          91.0      84.2     83.8          94.7   87.2   76.3      99.2\n GPT-4o-Audio                     95.6          89.8          91.6      75.5     80.2          89.2   84.1   76.0      98.7\n Kimi-Audio-Instruct              89.2          79.4          84.0      63.1     62.2          83.5   69.7   61.1      100.0\n MiMo-Audio                       75.0          64.6          63.5      36.3     52.8          66.2   68.4   69.5      98.3\n Baichuan-Audio                   88.2          81.6          78.4      45.8     53.2          71.7   54.8   50.3      99.4\n Phi-4-multimodal                 76.2          76.4          71.2      39.8     42.2          65.9   61.8   45.4      100.0\n Audex 30B-A3B                    87.4          82.7          78.2      60.2     82.6          91.0   88.0   88.0       99.6\n Audex 2B                         70.1          66.9          60.5      25.7     62.1          73.0   64.4   73.8       99.8\n\n\n\n\n6. Related Work\n6.1. Unified Understanding and Generation Models\nIt remains a challenging task to combine understanding and generation into a single LLM. This is caused by\nthe nature of significant distinctions between these tasks: generation requires synthesizing fine-grained details,\nwhile understanding is generally achievable with succinct semantic features. Furthermore, it remains a nascent,\nopen question on how to preserve strong text reasoning quality while adding unified multimodal capabilities.\n\nA number of studies have been conducted in the vision domain (Chen et al., 2025b; Tang et al., 2025; Team,\n2024; Wang et al., 2024c; Wu et al., 2026, 2025b; Ye et al., 2026; Zhang et al., 2025b; Zhuang et al., 2025).\nIn summary, while it is possible to integrate all the text and multimodal capabilities into a single model, it is\nchallenging to optimize all of them simultaneously – gains on certain tasks may lead to degradations on other\ntasks (especially the text reasoning quality). Several works demonstrate that fusing multimodal data in early\n\n\n                                                                                                                               17\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nstages (such as pre-training) helps unified modeling (Team, 2024; Team et al., 2026), and the MoE architecture\nalso helps (Tong et al., 2026). Several works use diffusion heads to handle the generation part (Chen et al.,\n2025a; Deng et al., 2025; Xie et al., 2025; Zhou et al., 2025); this approach is orthogonal to our work.\n\nThe unification of understanding and generation is less studied in the general audio domain. Our previous\nwork, UALM (Tian et al., 2026), took a first step towards this direction. With proper data blending and\ntraining recipes, UALM-7B achieves the state-of-the-art text-to-audio generation, matches the strong audio\nunderstanding models at the same size, and has small degradation on several text benchmarks including MMLU\n(Hendrycks et al., 2020), GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), and HumanEval (Chen et al., 2021) compared to the\nbase LLM. However, UALM’s study on text benchmarks have limitations in terms of the following two aspects:\n(𝑖) the LLM evaluation domain is rapidly evolving and these three benchmarks get saturated, and (𝑖𝑖) UALM\nonly studies the effect of text SFT without text RL, and as a consequence, may exhibit limited performance on\ncomplex multi-step reasoning tasks.\n\nIn this work, we conduct a systematic study along this line and present Audex. Compared to UALM, Audex\nfurther improves text-to-audio and audio understanding quality, supports text-to-speech generation and speech\nrecognition, and achieves systematically better text reasoning abilities along with a comprehensive study on\nthe effect of text SFT+RL. Notably, Audex is comparable with the base LLM (Nemotron-Cascade 2 (Yang\net al., 2026)) on a wide range of text reasoning tasks including knowledge, chat, long context, and agentic\nbenchmarks. We present comprehensive and effective training recipes for audio and text modeling that lead to\nour results.\n\n6.2. Speech LLMs\nSpeech LLMs are a class of audio LLMs specialized for speech applications, including automatic speech\nrecognition (ASR), automatic speech translation (AST), speech understanding, text-to-speech (TTS) generation,\nspeech-to-speech (S2S) generation, and combinations of these tasks (Chen et al., 2024b; Défossez et al., 2024;\nHuang et al., 2023b; Kharitonov et al., 2023; Kim et al., 2024; Nguyen et al., 2025; Radford et al., 2022;\nRubenstein et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023a,b, 2024b, 2025d; Zhang et al., 2023a,b).\n\nThe speech outputs of speech LLMs are usually discrete speech tokens obtained from codec models (Défossez\net al., 2022, 2024; Gong et al., 2026; Ji et al., 2025; Kumar et al., 2023; Yang et al., 2023; Ye et al., 2025a,b;\nZeghidour et al., 2021; Zhang et al., 2024). Codec models are trained to encode speech waveforms into discrete\ntokens (or codebooks) and reconstruct waveform from these tokens, and are usually trained with the VQ-VAE\nstyle (Van Den Oord et al., 2017) Encoder-Quantizer-Decoder architectures. For efficient representation,\nhigher quality, and better latency, speech LLMs adopt various quantization methods such as residual vector\nquantization (RVQ) (Zeghidour et al., 2021) and finite scalar quantization (FSQ) (Mentzer et al., 2023), and\ndifferent codebook recipes and parallelized token patterns associated with them (Copet et al., 2024). Some\nworks also use a separate talker for better scalability and control (Xu et al., 2025a,b).\n\nThe inputs to speech LLMs are usually in various formats, including discrete tokens from speech codec models\n(Chen et al., 2024b; Wang et al., 2023a; Zhang et al., 2025a), continuous representations of an audio encoder\n(Goel et al., 2025; Liu et al., 2025a; Lu et al., 2026), or a hybrid format (Ding et al., 2025). These approaches\nusually have different trade-offs between improving the recognition/understanding quality versus reducing\ninput-output space mismatch.\n\nThere is another line of research called duplex models (ByteDance Seed Team, 2026; Casanova et al., 2025;\nChien et al., 2026; Défossez et al., 2024; Hu et al., 2025; Leviathan and Matias, 2018; Roy et al., 2026). These\nmodels focus on real-time interaction between the user and the agent, where both can speak-while-listen at the\nsame time. Duplex models are based on speech LLMs and introduce additional channels for interaction, which\nis outside the scope of this paper.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                               18\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\n6.3. Audio Understanding Models\nAudio understanding models extend speech LLMs to the domain of general non-speech sound and music,\nand focus on semantic understanding of these sound. The tasks include captioning, question-answering, and\nclassification in a wide range of perspectives. Especially, some works focus on non-speech sound understanding\n(Deshmukh et al., 2023, 2026b; Ghosh et al., 2024, 2025b; Kong et al., 2024a), music understanding (Deng\net al., 2024; Gardner et al., 2023; Ghosh et al., 2025a; Liu et al., 2024c; Ma et al., 2024; Won et al., 2024), or\nall types of sound including speech (Ding et al., 2025; Ghosh et al., 2026; Goel et al., 2025; Gong et al., 2023;\nLiu et al., 2025a; Tang et al., 2024; Team, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang\net al., 2025a). Some works also have speech outputs as discussed in the previous section (Ding et al., 2025;\nTeam, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\nMost of the audio understanding models take continuous representations from one or more audio encoders as\ninputs. There are many types of audio encoders used based on the focus and tasks of the audio understanding\nmodel (Chen et al., 2022a,b; Chu et al., 2024; Dhariwal et al., 2020; Elizalde et al., 2023; Goel et al., 2025;\nGong et al., 2021; Li et al., 2024b; Radford et al., 2022; Sekoyan et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2023; Xu et al., 2025b).\nBesides continuous representations, several works investigated audio understanding with discrete audio codecs,\nbut there is still a gap from the state-of-the-art models in terms of audio understanding quality (Yang et al.,\n2024; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\n6.4. Audio Generation Models\nUnlike speech generation models where the goal is to speak the transcriptions, audio generation models (or\ntext-to-audio models) focus on generating an audio clip that is semantically consistent with a given text prompt\n(e.g., The sound of river flows and birds chirping). This task is similar to text-to-image generation (Ramesh et al.,\n2021; Rombach et al., 2022) applied to the general audio domain.\n\nSome early approaches model text-to-audio generation with an LLM to predict discrete audio tokens (Agostinelli\net al., 2023; Borsos et al., 2023; Copet et al., 2024; Kreuk et al., 2022; Liu et al., 2025b). However, recent\nleading approach is largely dominated by diffusion-based models (Chen et al., 2024a; Evans et al., 2024;\nGhosal et al., 2023; Huang et al., 2023a; Hung et al., 2024; Lee et al., 2025; Liu et al., 2023; Majumder et al.,\n2024) in terms of sample quality, controllability, duration, and inference speed.\n\nOur previous work, UALM (Tian et al., 2026), aims to close the long-standing quality gap using LLM-based\nmethods for audio generation. With proper data scaling, classifier-free guidance (Ho and Salimans, 2022)\nat training and inference time, and a post-training curriculum, UALM presents state-of-the-art text-to-audio\nresults using 1.5B and 7B LLMs. In this work, we leverage the techniques developed in UALM, and further\nscale to our 30B MoE LLM backbone (Blakeman et al., 2025b).\n\n\n7. Acknowledgments\nWe would like to extend our gratitude to the broader NVIDIA team for valuable discussions. We thank Lukas\nVoegtle and Philipp Fischer for helpful discussions on the Megatron-Energon dataloader. We thank Boris\nGinsburg, Zhehuai Chen, Jason Li, Edresson Casanova, and Yongqiang Wang for helpful discussions on building\nspeech LLMs. We also thank Jinchuan Tian for his exploratory work during his internship.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                  19\n\f                            Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\n\nAppendix\nA. Benchmarks, Evaluation Setups, and Baselines\nWe include the details of benchmarks, evaluation setups, and baselines to make this technical report self-\ncontained.\n\nIn this work, we use the same evaluation setups as Nemotron-Cascade 2 (Yang et al., 2026) for text benchmarks\n(see Appendix A.1 – A.5). The evaluation setups for audio tasks are in Appendix A.6 – A.10; in these tasks, the\naudio understanding evaluations follow Audio Flamingo 3 (Goel et al., 2025), and the text-to-audio evaluations\nfollow ETTA (Lee et al., 2025).\n\nA.1. Reasoning\nFor math and code reasoning, we include\n\n  • AIME 2025 & 2026 (MAA, 2025, 2026): 30 & 30 problems from American Invitational Mathematics\n    Examination at 2025 and 2026, respectively.\n  • HMMT Feb 2025 (HMMT, 2025): 30 problems from Harvard-MIT Mathematics Tournament 2025 February\n    math competition.\n  • IMO-AnswerBench (Luong et al., 2025): 400 problems with verifiable answers carefully chosen from past\n    Olympiad competitions and then altered by experts to avoid memorization.\n  • LiveCodeBench (Jain et al., 2024) contains diverse algorithm coding problems with unit tests, collected\n    from AtCoder, LeetCode platforms. We evaluate models competitive coding capability on LiveCodeBench\n    v6 (2024/08-2025/05, 454 problems in total). We report pass@1 accuracy in thinking mode, averaged\n    over 8 generations (avg@8).\n  • SciCode (Tian et al., 2024) serves as a challenging benchmark to evaluate model’s ability on solving\n    realistic scientific research tasks from STEM domains. It contains 338 subproblems from 80 main tasks.\n\nFor Audex-30B-A3B and Nemotron-Cascade-2-30B-A3B evaluated on AIME 2025, AIME 2026, HMMT 2025\nFeb, and LiveCodeBench v6, we set the thinking budget (maximum response length) to 131K tokens, the\nsampling temperature to 1.0, the top-p value to 1.0. For the with-tool setting, we enable tool use by appending\na system-prompt postfix, allowing the model to call a stateful Python executor for up to 100 tool calls with a\nmaximum response length of 131K tokens. For IMO-AnswerBench, we set to 256K tokens because we found the\nquestions are significantly more difficult. We use and report the LLM-Judge score using GPT-OSS-120B (Agarwal\net al., 2025) as the judge and the AnswerAutoGrader prompt (Luong et al., 2025) for answer correctness on\nIMO-AnswerBench as the short answers are complicated for rule-based verifier to compute. Following Liu et al.\n(2024d, 2026), we report avg@64 for AIME/HMMT and avg@16 for IMO-AnswerBench.\n\nFor baseline models, we use official numbers from their reports if the official numbers are available. Otherwise,\nwe evaluate baseline models with the recommended settings, ensuring a thinking budget of at least 128K\ntokens.\n\nA.2. Knowledge\nFor knowledge reasoning, we include:\n\n  • MMLU-Redux (Gema et al., 2024) is a benchmark consisting of a subset of 3,000 manually re-annotated\n    questions across 30 MMLU subjects (Hendrycks et al., 2020), which eliminates the original annotation\n    errors. We evaluate the models in thinking mode and, due to the large test set size, report exact match (EM)\n    accuracy based on a single generation per question.\n  • MMLU-Pro (Wang et al., 2024d) is an enhanced version of the original MMLU benchmark that mitigates\n    model saturation by expanding to over 12,000 graduate-level questions and increasing answer choices\n    from four to ten. We report EM accuracy in thinking mode using one generation per question.\n\n\n                                                                                                              20\n\f                            Unified Audio Intelligence Without", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d/tool-results/bypmf66vr.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 38835}}
