{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-aef833b6420b187b", "type": "tool_result", "content": "<persisted-output>\nOutput too large (31.4KB). Full output saved to: /inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d/tool-results/b52nvqm00.txt\n\nPreview (first 2KB):\n   • State-of-the-art TTS models: Seed-TTS (Anastassiou et al., 2024), Step-Audio-TTS-3B 13 , E2 TTS (Eskimez\n     et al., 2024), F5 TTS (Chen et al., 2024c), and\n   • General-purpose audio language models: Qwen2.5 Omni (Xu et al., 2025a), Qwen3 Omni (Xu et al.,\n     2025b), MiMo-Audio (Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\nA.7. Speech Recognition and Speech-to-Text Translation\nFor ASR and AST tasks, we include:\n\n  • Open ASR (Srivastav et al., 2025) evaluates English ASR on AMI, Earnings22, GigaSpeech, LibriSpeech,\n    SPGISpeech, TED-LIUM, and VoxPopuli, spanning meetings, earnings calls, audiobooks, podcasts/web\n    audio, financial speech, talks, and parliamentary speech. We report WER using the official English\n    normalization pipeline.14\n  • Noisy ASR evaluates robustness to additive noise on LibriSpeech test-clean. Similar to the noisy ASR\n    evaluation in Canary-1B-v2 (Sekoyan et al., 2025), we synthesize noisy speech by mixing each clean\n    utterance with a randomly selected noise or background sound at SNR levels of −5, 0, 5, 10, 25, 50, and\n    100 dB. We report WER using the same English normalization pipeline as Open ASR.\n  • Multilingual Open ASR (Srivastav et al., 2025) evaluates multilingual speech recognition. We use\n    the FLEURS subset, including the five FLEURS languages in the leaderboard setting (German, Spanish,\n    French, Italian, and Portuguese), and additionally report Korean and Russian. We report WER using the\n    multilingual Open ASR normalization pipeline.14\n  • FLEURS speech-to-text translation (Conneau et al., 2023) evaluates X→English speech translation. We\n    use the same seven source languages as multilingual ASR and report BLEU (Papineni et al., 2002) and\n    COMET (Rei et al., 2020). 15\n\nFor OpenASR and Noisy ASR evaluation, Audex and all speech-LM baselines are evaluated with ASR prompts\nwithout the language id. The prompt for Audex is: <sound>∖nTranscribe the speech in the input audio. For\n...\n</persisted-output>", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d", "uuid": "265b5230-789b-40e1-892c-53e4310982fb", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:42:15.567Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "   • State-of-the-art TTS models: Seed-TTS (Anastassiou et al., 2024), Step-Audio-TTS-3B 13 , E2 TTS (Eskimez\n     et al., 2024), F5 TTS (Chen et al., 2024c), and\n   • General-purpose audio language models: Qwen2.5 Omni (Xu et al., 2025a), Qwen3 Omni (Xu et al.,\n     2025b), MiMo-Audio (Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\nA.7. Speech Recognition and Speech-to-Text Translation\nFor ASR and AST tasks, we include:\n\n  • Open ASR (Srivastav et al., 2025) evaluates English ASR on AMI, Earnings22, GigaSpeech, LibriSpeech,\n    SPGISpeech, TED-LIUM, and VoxPopuli, spanning meetings, earnings calls, audiobooks, podcasts/web\n    audio, financial speech, talks, and parliamentary speech. We report WER using the official English\n    normalization pipeline.14\n  • Noisy ASR evaluates robustness to additive noise on LibriSpeech test-clean. Similar to the noisy ASR\n    evaluation in Canary-1B-v2 (Sekoyan et al., 2025), we synthesize noisy speech by mixing each clean\n    utterance with a randomly selected noise or background sound at SNR levels of −5, 0, 5, 10, 25, 50, and\n    100 dB. We report WER using the same English normalization pipeline as Open ASR.\n  • Multilingual Open ASR (Srivastav et al., 2025) evaluates multilingual speech recognition. We use\n    the FLEURS subset, including the five FLEURS languages in the leaderboard setting (German, Spanish,\n    French, Italian, and Portuguese), and additionally report Korean and Russian. We report WER using the\n    multilingual Open ASR normalization pipeline.14\n  • FLEURS speech-to-text translation (Conneau et al., 2023) evaluates X→English speech translation. We\n    use the same seven source languages as multilingual ASR and report BLEU (Papineni et al., 2002) and\n    COMET (Rei et al., 2020). 15\n\nFor OpenASR and Noisy ASR evaluation, Audex and all speech-LM baselines are evaluated with ASR prompts\nwithout the language id. The prompt for Audex is: <sound>∖nTranscribe the speech in the input audio. For\nmultilingual ASR, we use language ids in the prompts for all models including Audex. For Audex, we add\n\"Language: {LANGUAGE_ID}\" to the previous prompt.\n\nFor AST, we specify the source language in user prompts for baseline models, but do not use the source language\nfor Audex. The prompt for Audex is: <sound>∖nTranslate the spoken content in the audio to English.\n\nAdditional details on prompting, decoding, and baseline-specific inference recipes are provided in Appendix D.\n\nThe baselines include:\n\n   • State-of-the-art ASR/AST models: Whisper-large-v3 (Radford et al., 2022), Seamless-m4t-v2-large\n     (Barrault et al., 2023), Canary-1B v2 (Sekoyan et al., 2025), Parakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3 (Sekoyan et al., 2025),\n     Canary-Qwen-2.5B 16 , and\n   • General-purpose audio language models: Step-Audio-R1.1 (Tian et al., 2025), Qwen3 Omni (Xu et al.,\n     2025b), MiMo-Audio (Zhang et al., 2025a), Kimi-Audio (Ding et al., 2025), Voxtral-Small (Liu et al.,\n     2025a).\n\nA.8. Speech Interaction\nWe evaluate on VoiceBench (Chen et al., 2026) and BigBenchAudio (Srivastava et al., 2022; Suzgun et al.,\n2022) for speech interaction tasks. We use a cascaded pipeline (ASR, text reasoning, and TTS) to evaluate\n  13 https://huggingface.co/stepfun-ai/Step-Audio-TTS-3B\n  14 https://github.com/huggingface/open_asr_leaderboard/tree/main/normalizer\n  15 COMET is computed with unbabel-comet v2.2.7 and the Unbabel/wmt22-comet-da checkpoint. https://github.com/\n\nUnbabel/COMET\n  16 https://huggingface.co/nvidia/canary-qwen-2.5b\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                            23\n\f                                Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\non these tasks, but different from prior cascaded systems that use different models (e.g. Whisper + GPT4o +\nTTS-1), each step of our pipeline uses the same Audex checkpoint with the recommended inference recipe as\ndescribed earlier. In detail, we first run Audex to get transcriptions similar to ASR evaluation. We then use\nAudex to run text reasoning similar to Reasoning and Knowledge benchmarks, with the following prompt:\n{TRANSCRIBED QUESTION} ∖n∖n Conclude your response with the sentence ‘The answer is ∖∖boxed{{X}}.‘ After\ntext reasoning is done, we extract the answer from the ∖∖boxed{{X}} outputs with some regex rules. For\nBigBenchAudio, we then generate speech samples using the transcription: The answer is {ANSWER}.\n\nThe baselines are taken from the BigBenchAudio Leaderboard 17 and VoiceBench Leaderboard 18 , and we\nadditionally evaluate Kimi-Audio-Instruct (Ding et al., 2025) and MiMo-Audio (Zhang et al., 2025a) on these\nbenchmarks.\n\nA.9. Audio Understanding\nFor audio understanding evaluation, we evaluate on the following benchmarks:\n\n   • MMAU (v05.15.25) (Sakshi et al., 2024), MMAR (Ma et al., 2025), and MMSU (Wang et al., 2025b) for\n     general sound, speech, and music understanding. These benchmarks are all multiple choice questions.\n     The prompt we use to evaluate Audex is: <sound>∖n{QUESTION} Choose the correct option from the\n     following options:∖n(A) {CHOICE A}∖n(B) {CHOICE B}∖n(C) {CHOICE C}∖n(D) {CHOICE D}.\n   • Audio Entailment (Deshmukh et al., 2024) on Clotho-v2 and AudioCaps for deductive reasoning. These\n     benchmarks contain closed-ended questions and require outputs to be within {yes, no, maybe}. The\n     prompt we use to evaluate Audex is: <sound>∖nIs the following description true about the input audio?\n     Answer in Yes, No or Maybe.∖nDescription: {DESCRIPTION}.\n   • CMM (Leng et al., 2026) for hallucination detection. This benchmark also contains closed-ended questions\n     with a focus on sound event existence, and requires outputs to be within {yes, no}. The prompt we use\n     to evaluate Audex is: <sound>∖nDid you hear {SOUND EVENT} in the audio?\n\nThe baselines include Audio Flamingo 3 (Goel et al., 2025), Step-Audio-R1.1 (Tian et al., 2025), Kimi-Audio\n(Ding et al., 2025), Voxtral-small (Liu et al., 2025a), MiMo-Audio (Zhang et al., 2025a), and Qwen3-Omni-\n30B-A3B instruct/thinking models (Xu et al., 2025b).\n\nA.10. Text-to-Audio\nFor TTA evaluation, we use the AudioCaps (Kim et al., 2019) and SongDescriber (Manco et al., 2023) bench-\nmarks. We evaluate on 10-second clips following the evaluation setup in ETTA (Lee et al., 2025). The template\nis: <|text to audio|> Generate audio for this caption. {CAPTION}.\n\nWe report the Fréchet Distance measured in OpenL3 feature space (Cramer et al., 2019), noted as following\nprior works (Evans et al., 2024; Lee et al., 2025). This metric, noted as FDopenl3 , measures the distance\nbetween the generated audio distribution and the reference set distribution, and is therefore the lower the\nmore statistically realistic.\n\nThe baselines include:\n\n   • Diffusion models: AudioLDM2 Large (Liu et al., 2024b), Stable Audio Open (Evans et al., 2024), ETTA\n     (Lee et al., 2025), Tango2 (Majumder et al., 2024), and TangoFlux (Hung et al., 2024);\n   • Autoregressive models tailored for audio generation: MusicGen (Copet et al., 2024), Magenta Realtime\n     (Team et al., 2025) 19 , UALM-Gen (Tian et al., 2026), and\n   • Versatile LLMs with audio generation capabilities: UALM (Tian et al., 2026).\n  17 https://artificialanalysis.ai/speech-to-speech#speech-reasoning\n  18 https://matthewcym.github.io/VoiceBench\n  19 MusicGen and Magenta Realtime are trained on licensed corpora.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                          24\n\f                                   Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nB. Detailed Results Across Training Stages\nTable 15 includes Audex-30B-A3B results at intermediate training stages. The Audio Gen. SFT stage achieves the\nbest AudioCaps results, along with very good SongDescriber and Seed-TTS-Eval results. After the Audio Gen. +\nAudio Und. SFT stage, TTS and SongDescriber results are better, and the model has strong audio understanding,\nASR, and AST abilities. In both stages, the text abilities are kept across a variety of benchmarks.\n\nDuring the RL stage, we observe that the text benchmarks improve in correspondence to the specific RL stages.\nMeanwhile, we do not see huge degradations in audio-related benchmarks. The only exception is that MOPD\ndegrades ASR and MMSU, but the results get recovered after two more RL stages. The other audio benchmarks\nare mostly stable during these RL stages, verifying that Nemotron Cascade-2 RL on specific text domains does\nnot affect multimodal abilities much.\n\nTable 15: Audex-30B-A3B Intermediate Stage Results. LS represents LibriSpeech ASR and is evaluated with\nWER. Fleurs (xx→en)4 is the averaged BLEU|COMET scores of AST across four languages (de, fr, it, es).\nSeed-TTS-Eval is evaluated with WER, where the numbers in parenthesis indicate fixed-voice TTS. AudioCaps\nand SongDescriber are evaluated with OpenL3 Fréchet Distance. We mark tool-integrated reasoning results\nwith ♢ for math and code reasoning.\n\n                Training Stages                               Benchmarks Results at Different Stages\n\n                                                                       (Part 1) Text Benchmarks\n\n                                         AIME 2025         HMMT Feb25      LiveCodeBench v6       MMLU-Pro      GPQA-Diamond\n                 Audio Gen. SFT         91.1|94.5♢         91.0|88.1♢          81.8|85.7                78.1         72.8\n   Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT          91.7|96.3♢         92.2|91.4♢          82.3|85.3                77.5         73.8\n        Instruction-Following RL             –                  –                  –                     –            –\n                Multi-domain RL              –                  –                  –                     –            –\n                          MOPD          92.8|98.4♢         95.1|92.9♢          85.9|87.4                78.2         74.2\n                           RLHF              –                  –                  –                     –            –\n       Long-context RL (Audex)          91.2|98.3♢         92.2|93.8♢          85.3|86.2                78.9         74.9\n\n                                                                       (Part 2) Text Benchmarks\n\n                                          IFBench          ArenaHard v2         AA-LCR             𝜏 2 -Bench    MMLU-Redux\n                 Audio Gen. SFT             50.9               67.7               23.7                  51.1         85.5\n   Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT              52.4               59.4               27.0                  52.4         86.3\n        Instruction-Following RL            78.0               52.2                –                     –            –\n                Multi-domain RL             78.5               48.8                –                    49.3          –\n                          MOPD              80.2               75.7               33.3                  56.5         85.6\n                           RLHF             77.7               81.7                –                    54.7          –\n       Long-context RL (Audex)              77.8               81.6               39.3                  57.2         86.4\n\n                                                                      (Part 3) Speech Benchmarks\n\n                                     LS (clean|others) ↓   LS (noisy) ↓     Fleurs (xx→en)4     BigBenchAudio   Seed-TTS-Eval ↓\n                 Audio Gen. SFT             N/S                N/S                N/S                   N/S          2.28\n   Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT           1.33|2.99             2.75            33.9|86.9                88.0      2.07(1.76)\n        Instruction-Following RL         1.34|3.03             2.77            33.8|86.9                88.9        (1.75)\n                Multi-domain RL          1.36|3.06             2.73            33.8|86.9                90.9        (1.76)\n                          MOPD           1.32|3.19             3.32            33.8|86.9                90.0        (1.80)\n                           RLHF          1.36|3.00             3.03            33.9|87.0                89.7        (1.93)\n       Long-context RL (Audex)           1.34|3.06             2.92            33.8|87.0                90.0        (1.70)\n\n                                                                      (Part 4) Audio Benchmarks\n\n                                        MMAU-mini             MMAR               MMSU             AudioCaps ↓   SongDescriber ↓\n                 Audio Gen. SFT             N/S                N/S                N/S                   59.3         65.7\n   Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT              76.3               62.7               63.3                  60.9         58.1\n        Instruction-Following RL            76.5               62.0               62.9                  65.3         59.9\n                Multi-domain RL             76.3               61.6               63.0                  64.2         59.6\n                          MOPD              77.2               63.2               60.9                  64.2         61.3\n                           RLHF             77.4               63.2               63.1                  64.3         61.1\n       Long-context RL (Audex)              76.5               63.2               63.4                  66.9         62.7\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                  25\n\f                                          Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nC. Ablation Studies\nC.1. Audio Warmup\nIn this section, we compare different audio warmup methods in multi-stage SFT. The first (used on Audex) is\nto freeze text token embeddings and only update audio token embeddings. This is implemented by gradient\nmasking of text token embeddings. Since LLM is also frozen, this approach does not affect the text part of the\nmodel. The second approach is to simply unfreeze both text and audio token embeddings and train on all tasks\nincluding text. We hypothesized this approach could jointly optimize all embeddings for better multi-modal\ntraining. The third approach is to combine the previous two: we apply the first and then the second.\n\nThe results after audio warmup are shown in Table 16. We find unfreezing text token embeddings has no\nbenefit in any situation, and the gap to the first approach is huge. In Table 5, we plot the text evaluation\nresults of the Audio Gen. SFT stage after different warmup methods. If we freeze the text embeddings in\nAudio Warmup, then the model begins with high text scores and have small degradation at the beginning of\nAudio Gen. SFT in compensation for the audio generation tasks. If we unfreeze the text embeddings, then the\nmodel begins with lower text scores, recovers after 10%-20% of training, but is not comparable with the first\napproach.\n\n\nTable 16: Comparison of Audio Warmup Methods.\n\n                       Warmup Method                                                       MMLU-Pro        GPQA-Diamond                AIME 2025\n                       Freeze text embeddings (Audex’s recipe)                                  78.9           73.8                      93.2\n                       Unfreeze all embeddings                                                  71.2           62.3                      71.8\n                       Freeze text embeddings then unfreeze all embeddings                      65.1            –                         –\n                       Unfreeze all embeddings; higher text weights                             59.7            –                         –\n\n\n\n                        Freeze        Unfreeze                                    Freeze        Unfreeze                                  Freeze          Unfreeze\n                                                        GPQA-Diamond\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                             90\n                                                                                                                 AIME 2025\n  MMLU-Pro\n\n\n\n\n                                                                       70\n             75\n                                                                                                                             80\n                                                                       65\n             70\n                                                                                                                             70\n                   0   20   40   60    80 100                                0   20   40   60    80 100                            0     20     40   60    80 100\n                  Audio Gen. SFT Progress (%)                               Audio Gen. SFT Progress (%)                           Audio Gen. SFT Progress (%)\n\nFigure 5: Audio Gen. SFT Results between Freezing and Unfreezing Text Embeddings in Audio Warmup.\n\n\nC.2. Text Data Blending Ratios\nIn this section, we ablate the blending ratios for text data and investigate how this ratio affects text quality in\nthe SFT training.\n\nIn Figure 6, we compare two text blending ratios: 0.56 vs 0.69 in the Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT stage. If the\ntext blending ratio is 0.56 (close to 0.59 in the Audio Gen. SFT stage), there is considerable degradation on text\nevaluation. This is potentially because in the Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT stage, there are many audio-text\npairs with text outputs; in contrast, in the Audio Gen. SFT stage, there is no text output for audio tasks, and\ntherefore, we need a higher text blending ratio in the Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT stage to maintain the text\nquality.\n\nIn Figure 7, we demonstrate the text benchmark evaluations of the single-stage consolidated SFT model through\nthe training progress. We begin with a text blending ratio of 0.75 (marked in blue), but observe significant cliff\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                     26\n\f                                                     Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\n                           0.69               0.56                                       0.69         0.56                                  0.69    0.56\n\n\n\n\n                                                                 GPQA-Diamond\n           78\n                                                                                72\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                       AIME 2025\nMMLU-Pro\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                   91\n           77\n                                                                                71\n                                                                                                                                   90\n           76\n                0       10                   20      30                              0   10        20        30                         0   10     20      30\nAudio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT Progress (%)                            Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT Progress (%) Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT Progress (%)\n\nFigure 6: Comparison of Text Data Blending Ratios (0.56 vs 0.69) in the Audio Gen. + Audio Und. SFT Stage.\n\n\nof the text evaluation results around 50%-60% of training (marked in red). We re-started from the checkpoint\nbefore the cliff (the last blue point) with different random seeds and observed cliff again around 60%-80% of\ntraining. We therefore increase the text blending ratio to 0.88 (marked in green), re-start from the last blue\npoint, and observe mild or no text degradations. We conclude that the single-stage consolidated SFT requires a\nsignificantly higher text blending ratio to keep the text quality, and this still does not alleviate the long-context\nissue discussed in Section 4.4.2.\n\n                                                                   0.88 (continued)            0.75 (continued)   0.75 (initial)\n\n                                   80\n                    MMLU-Pro\n\n\n\n\n                                   75\n\n                                   70\n\n                                   65\n\n                                        20                     40                         60                      80                        100\n                                                          Audio Gen. + Audio Und. + Text Consolidated SFT Progress (%)\n                                                                     0.88 (continued)          0.75 (continued)    0.75 (initial)\n                    GPQA-Diamond\n\n\n\n\n                                   70\n\n\n                                   60\n\n\n\n                                        20                      40                            60                  80                        100\n                                                          Audio Gen. + Audio Und. + Text Consolidated SFT Progress (%)\n                                                                   0.88 (continued)            0.75 (continued)   0.75 (initial)\n\n                                   90\n                    AIME 2025\n\n\n\n\n                                   80\n\n                                   70\n\n                                        20                     40                         60                      80                        100\n                                                          Audio Gen. + Audio Und. + Text Consolidated SFT Progress (%)\n\nFigure 7: Comparison of Text Data Blending Ratios (0.75 vs 0.88) in the Single-Stage Consolidated SFT Stage.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                27\n\f                                                                Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nC.3. CFG Values and Hyper-parameters for TTS and TTA\nIn this section, we study the optimal inference hyper-parameters for TTA (Figure 8) and TTS (Figure 9). We\nfind for TTA, the best CFG value 𝜆 ∈ [3, 5] and use 𝜆 = 3 in our experiments. We find the best Top-k to be 80\nand temperature to be 1.0. For TTS, the best CFG value 𝜆 ≈ 1.5 and use 𝜆 = 1.5 in our experiments. We also\nfind the WER is close to optimal even without CFG. We find the best Top-k to be 80 and temperature to be 0.1.\n\n                           Audiocaps                Song Describer                                     0.6         0.8         1.0                              0.6      0.8         1.0\n\n\n                                                                                          150                                                      100\n\n\n\n\n                                                                             FDopenl3 ↓\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                      FDopenl3 ↓\n              80\n FDopenl3 ↓\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                    80\n              70                                                                          100\n\n\n              60                                                                                                                                    60\n                                                                                           50\n                       1       2   3    4       5       6   7    8                              20      40     80        160   320                       20     40     80      160   320\n\n                                            𝜆                                                                Top-k                                                    Top-k\n (a) FDopenl3 vs CFG 𝜆 (Top-k = 80,                                          (b) FDopenl3 vs Top-k on Audio-                          (c) FDopenl3 vs Top-k on Song De-\n temperature 𝑡 = 1.0)                                                        Caps at different temperature 𝑡 ∈                        scriber at different temperature 𝑡 ∈\n                                                                             {0.6, 0.8, 1.0}.                                         {0.6, 0.8, 1.0}.\n\nFigure 8: Comparisons across different inference hyperparameters for text-to-audio generation.\n\n                                                                                                     0.05      0.10            0.15                             20        40         80\n                                       Seed-TTS-Eval (en)                                            0.20      0.30                                            160       320\n\n\n                   3\n                                                                                          1.7                                                      1.7\n                                                                             WER ↓\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                      WER ↓\n     WER ↓\n\n\n\n\n              2.5\n                                                                                          1.6                                                      1.6\n                   2\n\n              1.5                                                                         1.5                                                      1.5\n                           1       2     3          4       5        6                          20     40     80     160       320                            0.10      0.20         0.30\n                                             𝜆                                                               Top-k                                            Temperature 𝑡\n (a) WER vs CFG 𝜆 on Seed-TTS-Eval                                           (b) WER vs Top-k on Seed-TTS-                            (c) WER vs Temperature 𝑡 on\n (Top-k = 80, temperature 𝑡 = 0.1)                                           Eval at different temperature 𝑡 ∈                        Seed-TTS-Eval at different Top-k\n                                                                             {0.05, 0.10, 0.15, 0.20, 0.30}.                          ∈ {20, 40, 80, 160, 320}.\n\nFigure 9: Comparisons across different inference hyperparameters for text-to-speech generation.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                                                                                                            28\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nD. Additional Details for ASR and AST Evaluations\nAudex uses a chat-style template, where the user turn contains the task instruction and a <sound> placeholder,\nand a response in the assistant turn. For ASR, this response consists of language identification followed by the\ntranscription. For AST, it consists of source-language identification, source transcription, and English translation.\nIn language-conditioned multilingual ASR, we additionally teacher-force the language identification field to the\nknown source language and let Audex continue to generate the transcription. For AST, we do not teacher-force\nthe language field and instead let the model generate the full structured response.\n\nFor ASR-specific baselines, we use public results from the OpenASR leaderboard for Whisper Large v3, Canary-\n1B-v2, Parakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3, and Canary-Qwen-2.5B. For noisy and multilingual ASR evaluations of the\nbaselines, we use the same model-specific ASR inference recipe that reproduces the OpenASR setting, with\none small change for multilingual ASR that we provide the source-language information. Canary-1B-v2 and\nParakeet-TDT-0.6B-v3 are evaluated on the European FLEURS languages they support, and Korean is excluded\nfor these two models. For Canary-Qwen-2.5B, we only report English ASR results. Seamless-M4T v2 Large is\nreported for multilingual ASR and AST, using the source language as the generation target for ASR and English\nas the target for translation.\n\nFor speech/audio LLM baselines, we use task-specific prompts, summarized in Table 17. For Qwen3-Omni-30B-\nA3B (Instruct / Thinking), we follow the official ASR and AST prompts. For the Thinking variant, we strip the\nreasoning trace and score only the final answer. Step-Audio R1.1 is a reasoning model, and we evaluate it in\nthinking mode with reasoning-budget control following the Nemotron 3 Nano Omni setup (Deshmukh et al.,\n2026a). Specifically, we cap the thinking segment at 13000 tokens and allow a 1024-token grace budget after\nthe reasoning trace, while using task-specific ASR and translation prompts. Kimi-Audio Instruct is evaluated on\nOpenASR with its official ASR prompt, but we omit multilingual ASR and AST because the released model and\nexamples primarily target English and Chinese. Voxtral Small 24B is evaluated with its speech transcription\nand translation endpoints when applicable. For MiMo-Audio, we report the LibriSpeech test-clean number from\nthe paper, as we did not identify a comparable full-benchmark ASR/AST evaluation path using the released\ninference setup.\n\n Baseline                 Setting", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false, "persistedOutputPath": "/inspire/qb-ilm/project/video-generation/chenxie-25019/hyr/iHateTheWorld555.github.io/.claude-review/projects/-inspire-qb-ilm-project-video-generation-chenxie-25019-hyr-iHateTheWorld555-github-io/a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d/tool-results/b52nvqm00.txt", "persistedOutputSize": 32137}}
