{"type": "user", "message": {"role": "user", "content": [{"tool_use_id": "chatcmpl-tool-870c9405ae80157f", "type": "tool_result", "content": "6. Related Work\n6.1. Unified Understanding and Generation Models\nIt remains a challenging task to combine understanding and generation into a single LLM. This is caused by\nthe nature of significant distinctions between these tasks: generation requires synthesizing fine-grained details,\nwhile understanding is generally achievable with succinct semantic features. Furthermore, it remains a nascent,\nopen question on how to preserve strong text reasoning quality while adding unified multimodal capabilities.\n\nA number of studies have been conducted in the vision domain (Chen et al., 2025b; Tang et al., 2025; Team,\n2024; Wang et al., 2024c; Wu et al., 2026, 2025b; Ye et al., 2026; Zhang et al., 2025b; Zhuang et al., 2025).\nIn summary, while it is possible to integrate all the text and multimodal capabilities into a single model, it is\nchallenging to optimize all of them simultaneously – gains on certain tasks may lead to degradations on other\ntasks (especially the text reasoning quality). Several works demonstrate that fusing multimodal data in early\n\n\n                                                                                                                               17\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nstages (such as pre-training) helps unified modeling (Team, 2024; Team et al., 2026), and the MoE architecture\nalso helps (Tong et al., 2026). Several works use diffusion heads to handle the generation part (Chen et al.,\n2025a; Deng et al., 2025; Xie et al., 2025; Zhou et al., 2025); this approach is orthogonal to our work.\n\nThe unification of understanding and generation is less studied in the general audio domain. Our previous\nwork, UALM (Tian et al., 2026), took a first step towards this direction. With proper data blending and\ntraining recipes, UALM-7B achieves the state-of-the-art text-to-audio generation, matches the strong audio\nunderstanding models at the same size, and has small degradation on several text benchmarks including MMLU\n(Hendrycks et al., 2020), GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), and HumanEval (Chen et al., 2021) compared to the\nbase LLM. However, UALM’s study on text benchmarks have limitations in terms of the following two aspects:\n(𝑖) the LLM evaluation domain is rapidly evolving and these three benchmarks get saturated, and (𝑖𝑖) UALM\nonly studies the effect of text SFT without text RL, and as a consequence, may exhibit limited performance on\ncomplex multi-step reasoning tasks.\n\nIn this work, we conduct a systematic study along this line and present Audex. Compared to UALM, Audex\nfurther improves text-to-audio and audio understanding quality, supports text-to-speech generation and speech\nrecognition, and achieves systematically better text reasoning abilities along with a comprehensive study on\nthe effect of text SFT+RL. Notably, Audex is comparable with the base LLM (Nemotron-Cascade 2 (Yang\net al., 2026)) on a wide range of text reasoning tasks including knowledge, chat, long context, and agentic\nbenchmarks. We present comprehensive and effective training recipes for audio and text modeling that lead to\nour results.\n\n6.2. Speech LLMs\nSpeech LLMs are a class of audio LLMs specialized for speech applications, including automatic speech\nrecognition (ASR), automatic speech translation (AST), speech understanding, text-to-speech (TTS) generation,\nspeech-to-speech (S2S) generation, and combinations of these tasks (Chen et al., 2024b; Défossez et al., 2024;\nHuang et al., 2023b; Kharitonov et al., 2023; Kim et al., 2024; Nguyen et al., 2025; Radford et al., 2022;\nRubenstein et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023a,b, 2024b, 2025d; Zhang et al., 2023a,b).\n\nThe speech outputs of speech LLMs are usually discrete speech tokens obtained from codec models (Défossez\net al., 2022, 2024; Gong et al., 2026; Ji et al., 2025; Kumar et al., 2023; Yang et al., 2023; Ye et al., 2025a,b;\nZeghidour et al., 2021; Zhang et al., 2024). Codec models are trained to encode speech waveforms into discrete\ntokens (or codebooks) and reconstruct waveform from these tokens, and are usually trained with the VQ-VAE\nstyle (Van Den Oord et al., 2017) Encoder-Quantizer-Decoder architectures. For efficient representation,\nhigher quality, and better latency, speech LLMs adopt various quantization methods such as residual vector\nquantization (RVQ) (Zeghidour et al., 2021) and finite scalar quantization (FSQ) (Mentzer et al., 2023), and\ndifferent codebook recipes and parallelized token patterns associated with them (Copet et al., 2024). Some\nworks also use a separate talker for better scalability and control (Xu et al., 2025a,b).\n\nThe inputs to speech LLMs are usually in various formats, including discrete tokens from speech codec models\n(Chen et al., 2024b; Wang et al., 2023a; Zhang et al., 2025a), continuous representations of an audio encoder\n(Goel et al., 2025; Liu et al., 2025a; Lu et al., 2026), or a hybrid format (Ding et al., 2025). These approaches\nusually have different trade-offs between improving the recognition/understanding quality versus reducing\ninput-output space mismatch.\n\nThere is another line of research called duplex models (ByteDance Seed Team, 2026; Casanova et al., 2025;\nChien et al., 2026; Défossez et al., 2024; Hu et al., 2025; Leviathan and Matias, 2018; Roy et al., 2026). These\nmodels focus on real-time interaction between the user and the agent, where both can speak-while-listen at the\nsame time. Duplex models are based on speech LLMs and introduce additional channels for interaction, which\nis outside the scope of this paper.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                               18\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\n6.3. Audio Understanding Models\nAudio understanding models extend speech LLMs to the domain of general non-speech sound and music,\nand focus on semantic understanding of these sound. The tasks include captioning, question-answering, and\nclassification in a wide range of perspectives. Especially, some works focus on non-speech sound understanding\n(Deshmukh et al., 2023, 2026b; Ghosh et al., 2024, 2025b; Kong et al., 2024a), music understanding (Deng\net al., 2024; Gardner et al., 2023; Ghosh et al., 2025a; Liu et al., 2024c; Ma et al., 2024; Won et al., 2024), or\nall types of sound including speech (Ding et al., 2025; Ghosh et al., 2026; Goel et al., 2025; Gong et al., 2023;\nLiu et al., 2025a; Tang et al., 2024; Team, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang\net al., 2025a). Some works also have speech outputs as discussed in the previous section (Ding et al., 2025;\nTeam, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\nMost of the audio understanding models take continuous representations from one or more audio encoders as\ninputs. There are many types of audio encoders used based on the focus and tasks of the audio understanding\nmodel (Chen et al., 2022a,b; Chu et al., 2024; Dhariwal et al., 2020; Elizalde et al., 2023; Goel et al., 2025;\nGong et al., 2021; Li et al., 2024b; Radford et al., 2022; Sekoyan et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2023; Xu et al., 2025b).\nBesides continuous representations, several works investigated audio understanding with discrete audio codecs,\nbut there is still a gap from the state-of-the-art models in terms of audio understanding quality (Yang et al.,\n2024; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\n6.4. Audio Generation Models\nUnlike speech generation models where the goal is to speak the transcriptions, audio generation models (or\ntext-to-audio models) focus on generating an audio clip that is semantically consistent with a given text prompt\n(e.g., The sound of river flows and birds chirping). This task is similar to text-to-image generation (Ramesh et al.,\n2021; Rombach et al., 2022) applied to the general audio domain.\n\nSome early approaches model text-to-audio generation with an LLM to predict discrete audio tokens (Agostinelli\net al., 2023; Borsos et al., 2023; Copet et al., 2024; Kreuk et al., 2022; Liu et al., 2025b). However, recent", "is_error": false}]}, "parent_tool_use_id": null, "session_id": "a1fa44bb-3e08-4f4d-a57c-6b7b1e63100d", "uuid": "80f59be3-870e-43ba-9edf-59fdb465168e", "timestamp": "2026-07-07T10:43:05.728Z", "tool_use_result": {"stdout": "6. Related Work\n6.1. Unified Understanding and Generation Models\nIt remains a challenging task to combine understanding and generation into a single LLM. This is caused by\nthe nature of significant distinctions between these tasks: generation requires synthesizing fine-grained details,\nwhile understanding is generally achievable with succinct semantic features. Furthermore, it remains a nascent,\nopen question on how to preserve strong text reasoning quality while adding unified multimodal capabilities.\n\nA number of studies have been conducted in the vision domain (Chen et al., 2025b; Tang et al., 2025; Team,\n2024; Wang et al., 2024c; Wu et al., 2026, 2025b; Ye et al., 2026; Zhang et al., 2025b; Zhuang et al., 2025).\nIn summary, while it is possible to integrate all the text and multimodal capabilities into a single model, it is\nchallenging to optimize all of them simultaneously – gains on certain tasks may lead to degradations on other\ntasks (especially the text reasoning quality). Several works demonstrate that fusing multimodal data in early\n\n\n                                                                                                                               17\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\nstages (such as pre-training) helps unified modeling (Team, 2024; Team et al., 2026), and the MoE architecture\nalso helps (Tong et al., 2026). Several works use diffusion heads to handle the generation part (Chen et al.,\n2025a; Deng et al., 2025; Xie et al., 2025; Zhou et al., 2025); this approach is orthogonal to our work.\n\nThe unification of understanding and generation is less studied in the general audio domain. Our previous\nwork, UALM (Tian et al., 2026), took a first step towards this direction. With proper data blending and\ntraining recipes, UALM-7B achieves the state-of-the-art text-to-audio generation, matches the strong audio\nunderstanding models at the same size, and has small degradation on several text benchmarks including MMLU\n(Hendrycks et al., 2020), GSM8K (Cobbe et al., 2021), and HumanEval (Chen et al., 2021) compared to the\nbase LLM. However, UALM’s study on text benchmarks have limitations in terms of the following two aspects:\n(𝑖) the LLM evaluation domain is rapidly evolving and these three benchmarks get saturated, and (𝑖𝑖) UALM\nonly studies the effect of text SFT without text RL, and as a consequence, may exhibit limited performance on\ncomplex multi-step reasoning tasks.\n\nIn this work, we conduct a systematic study along this line and present Audex. Compared to UALM, Audex\nfurther improves text-to-audio and audio understanding quality, supports text-to-speech generation and speech\nrecognition, and achieves systematically better text reasoning abilities along with a comprehensive study on\nthe effect of text SFT+RL. Notably, Audex is comparable with the base LLM (Nemotron-Cascade 2 (Yang\net al., 2026)) on a wide range of text reasoning tasks including knowledge, chat, long context, and agentic\nbenchmarks. We present comprehensive and effective training recipes for audio and text modeling that lead to\nour results.\n\n6.2. Speech LLMs\nSpeech LLMs are a class of audio LLMs specialized for speech applications, including automatic speech\nrecognition (ASR), automatic speech translation (AST), speech understanding, text-to-speech (TTS) generation,\nspeech-to-speech (S2S) generation, and combinations of these tasks (Chen et al., 2024b; Défossez et al., 2024;\nHuang et al., 2023b; Kharitonov et al., 2023; Kim et al., 2024; Nguyen et al., 2025; Radford et al., 2022;\nRubenstein et al., 2023; Wang et al., 2023a,b, 2024b, 2025d; Zhang et al., 2023a,b).\n\nThe speech outputs of speech LLMs are usually discrete speech tokens obtained from codec models (Défossez\net al., 2022, 2024; Gong et al., 2026; Ji et al., 2025; Kumar et al., 2023; Yang et al., 2023; Ye et al., 2025a,b;\nZeghidour et al., 2021; Zhang et al., 2024). Codec models are trained to encode speech waveforms into discrete\ntokens (or codebooks) and reconstruct waveform from these tokens, and are usually trained with the VQ-VAE\nstyle (Van Den Oord et al., 2017) Encoder-Quantizer-Decoder architectures. For efficient representation,\nhigher quality, and better latency, speech LLMs adopt various quantization methods such as residual vector\nquantization (RVQ) (Zeghidour et al., 2021) and finite scalar quantization (FSQ) (Mentzer et al., 2023), and\ndifferent codebook recipes and parallelized token patterns associated with them (Copet et al., 2024). Some\nworks also use a separate talker for better scalability and control (Xu et al., 2025a,b).\n\nThe inputs to speech LLMs are usually in various formats, including discrete tokens from speech codec models\n(Chen et al., 2024b; Wang et al., 2023a; Zhang et al., 2025a), continuous representations of an audio encoder\n(Goel et al., 2025; Liu et al., 2025a; Lu et al., 2026), or a hybrid format (Ding et al., 2025). These approaches\nusually have different trade-offs between improving the recognition/understanding quality versus reducing\ninput-output space mismatch.\n\nThere is another line of research called duplex models (ByteDance Seed Team, 2026; Casanova et al., 2025;\nChien et al., 2026; Défossez et al., 2024; Hu et al., 2025; Leviathan and Matias, 2018; Roy et al., 2026). These\nmodels focus on real-time interaction between the user and the agent, where both can speak-while-listen at the\nsame time. Duplex models are based on speech LLMs and introduce additional channels for interaction, which\nis outside the scope of this paper.\n\n\n\n\n                                                                                                               18\n\f                             Unified Audio Intelligence Without Regressing on Text Intelligence\n\n\n\n6.3. Audio Understanding Models\nAudio understanding models extend speech LLMs to the domain of general non-speech sound and music,\nand focus on semantic understanding of these sound. The tasks include captioning, question-answering, and\nclassification in a wide range of perspectives. Especially, some works focus on non-speech sound understanding\n(Deshmukh et al., 2023, 2026b; Ghosh et al., 2024, 2025b; Kong et al., 2024a), music understanding (Deng\net al., 2024; Gardner et al., 2023; Ghosh et al., 2025a; Liu et al., 2024c; Ma et al., 2024; Won et al., 2024), or\nall types of sound including speech (Ding et al., 2025; Ghosh et al., 2026; Goel et al., 2025; Gong et al., 2023;\nLiu et al., 2025a; Tang et al., 2024; Team, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang\net al., 2025a). Some works also have speech outputs as discussed in the previous section (Ding et al., 2025;\nTeam, 2026; Tian et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2025a; Xu et al., 2025a,b; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\nMost of the audio understanding models take continuous representations from one or more audio encoders as\ninputs. There are many types of audio encoders used based on the focus and tasks of the audio understanding\nmodel (Chen et al., 2022a,b; Chu et al., 2024; Dhariwal et al., 2020; Elizalde et al., 2023; Goel et al., 2025;\nGong et al., 2021; Li et al., 2024b; Radford et al., 2022; Sekoyan et al., 2025; Wu et al., 2023; Xu et al., 2025b).\nBesides continuous representations, several works investigated audio understanding with discrete audio codecs,\nbut there is still a gap from the state-of-the-art models in terms of audio understanding quality (Yang et al.,\n2024; Zhang et al., 2025a).\n\n6.4. Audio Generation Models\nUnlike speech generation models where the goal is to speak the transcriptions, audio generation models (or\ntext-to-audio models) focus on generating an audio clip that is semantically consistent with a given text prompt\n(e.g., The sound of river flows and birds chirping). This task is similar to text-to-image generation (Ramesh et al.,\n2021; Rombach et al., 2022) applied to the general audio domain.\n\nSome early approaches model text-to-audio generation with an LLM to predict discrete audio tokens (Agostinelli\net al., 2023; Borsos et al., 2023; Copet et al., 2024; Kreuk et al., 2022; Liu et al., 2025b). However, recent", "stderr": "", "interrupted": false, "isImage": false, "noOutputExpected": false}}
